<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06262096 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06262096 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  BRIEF; PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Toronto reliever David Weathers walked Jay Buhner with the bases loaded andtwo out in the 11th inning Tuesday night, giving the Seattle Mariners a 5-4victory and cutting the Blue Jays' lead in the A.L. East to 2 1/2 games.;  Relief ace Tom Henke blew a save chance for the second straight day and theBlue Jays went on to lose their third in a row. Boston had not been within 21/2 games of Toronto since June 28.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MARINERS CUT DOWN JAYS IN 11  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  A.L. Roundup  </MEMO><TEXT>     Henke, who had converted 32 of 33 save opportunities before this seriesbegan, took over to start the ninth with a 4-3 lead. But Harold Reynolds ledoff with a triple and scored the tying run on Pete O'Brien's one-out singleoff the glove of drawn-in second baseman Roberto Alomar.;   The Marinersloaded the bases in the 11th on Greg Briley's single off Jim Acker, asacrifice by Reynolds, an intentional walk to Ken Griffey Jr. and O'Brien'swalk from reliever Bob MacDonald.;   MacDonald struck out Alvin Davis, butWeathers relieved and walked Buhner on a 3-and-2 pitch.; RED SOX 4, ORIOLES 3:Jack Clark's wind-blown home run broke a sixth-inning tie and Jeff Reardonprotected the lead for his 40th save as host Boston beat Baltimore.;   The RedSox, who had lost four of five to Baltimore at Fenway Park, won for the 11thtime in 14 games.;   With the score tied 3-3, Clark hit the first pitch in thebottom of the sixth to right. The opposite-field fly got caught in a crosswindand landed in the seats, just out of Dwight Evans' reach near the 302-footmark, for Clark's 23rd home run.; OTHER GAMES: Doug Jones struck out acareer-high 13 batters as the host Cleveland Indians beat Detroit 3-1. TheTigers are five games behind Toronto in the A.L. East. . . . Bret Saberhagenoutpitched Jack Morris as the Kansas City Royals beat the Minnesota Twins 4-1in Minneapolis. . . . Chris Bosio pitched a two-hitter to lead the MilwaukeeBrewers to a 2-0 win over the host New York Yankees. . . . Wally Joyner drovein three runs as the California Angels defeated the Texas Rangers 7-2 inArlington, Texas.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910918  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  387  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, September 18, 199100262096,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>